# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autonomous-vehicles
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] As most road crashes occur due to human error, ADAS are developed to automate, adapt, and enhance vehicle technology for safety and better driving.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS is proven to reduce road fatalities by minimizing human error.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Safety features are designed to avoid crashes and collisions by offering technologies that alert the driver to problems, implementing safeguards, and taking control of the vehicle if necessary.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] According to the national crash database in the US, forward collision prevention systems have the potential to reduce crashes by 29%.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Similarly, lane keeping assistance is shown to offer a reduction potential of 19%, while blind zone detection could decrease crash incidents by 9%.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] According to a 2021 research report from Canalys, approximately 33% of new vehicles sold in the United States, Europe, Japan, and China had ADAS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The firm also predicted that 50% of all automobiles on the road by the year 2030 would be ADAS-enabled.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Some groups advocate standardization of the name, such as "forward collision warning" and "automatic emergency braking", rather than "forward collision alert" or "smart city brake support".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Such standardization is promoted by AAA, Consumer Reports, J.D.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Power, National Safety Council, PAVE, and SAE International.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] After WWII, an engineer named Nathaniel Korman, who worked on radar systems during WWII, experimented with a system to control the speed of a train based on the speed of a train in front of it, using radar.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] He noted that it could also be used for on-road vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In 1948, Ralph Teetor applied for a US patent in a "speed control device for resisting operation of the accelerator", or what is now known as cruise control, granted in 1950.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] General Motors later displayed a concept car in 1959, which used some variation of the system, with radar embedded in the front nacelles of the car.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS were first used in production vehicles in the 1970s with the adoption of the anti-lock braking system.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Early ADAS include electronic stability control, anti-lock brakes, blind spot information systems, lane departure warning, adaptive cruise control, and traction control.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems can be affected by mechanical alignment adjustments or damage from a collision.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This has led many manufacturers to require automatic resets for these systems after a mechanical alignment is performed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The reliance on data that describes the outside environment of the vehicle, compared to internal data, differentiates ADAS from driver-assistance systems (DAS).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS rely on inputs from multiple data sources, including automotive imaging, LiDAR, radar, image processing, computer vision, telemetry, and in-car networking.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Additional inputs are possible from other sources separate from the primary vehicle platform, such as telematics data from other vehicles (vehicle-to-vehicle or V2V communication) and infrastructure (vehicle-to-infrastructure or V2I communication).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Modern cars have ADAS integrated into their electronics; manufacturers can add these new features during the design process or after production via over-the-air (OTA) updates.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS are considered real-time systems since they react quickly to multiple inputs and prioritize the incoming information to prevent crashes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The systems use preemptive priority scheduling to organize which task needs to be done first.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The incorrect assignment of these priorities is what can cause more harm than good.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The SAE classification of levels is based on the role of the driver, rather than the vehicle's capabilities, although these are related in the form of a "driving mode" (also known as a "driving scenario").
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The mode is determined by both an operational design domain (ODD) and a "dynamic driving requirement".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The ODD is the circumstance in which the car is driving, and the driving requirement is what the system must do while remaining safe within the boundaries of that ODD.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] While most ADAS features are installed by the vehicle manufacturer during production (OEM), there is a growing market for aftermarket systems that can be retrofitted to existing vehicles, particularly in commercial fleets.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems are designed to provide key safety alerts and warnings to drivers of vehicles that were not originally equipped with ADAS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The most common type of aftermarket ADAS is based on computer vision and utilizes a windshield-mounted camera.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This device, which often combines the functionality of a dashcam with ADAS software, continuously scans the road ahead.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Sometimes they are referred as AI Dashcams.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems are often a component of modern video telematics, as they not only provide safety alerts but also record video footage of the events.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This data is then transmitted via a telematic control unit to a fleet management platform, where it can be used for driver coaching and incident analysis.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This list is not a comprehensive list of all of the ADAS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Instead, it provides information on critical examples of ADAS that have progressed and become more commonly available since 2015.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Ford and General Motors provide "hands-off, eyes-on" systems such as Blue Cruise and Super Cruise in North America.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems allow drivers to take their hands off the steering wheel while the system is engaged.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] However, drivers must keep their eyes on the road and be ready to take immediate action at all times.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In Europe, in Q2 2018, 3% of sold passenger cars had Level 2 autonomy driving features.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In Europe, in Q2 2019, 325,000 passenger cars are sold with Level 2 autonomy driving features, that is 8% of all new cars sold.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] According to a 2021 research report from Canalys, approximately 33 percent of new vehicles sold in the United States, Europe, Japan, and China had ADAS features.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The firm also predicted that fifty percent of all automobiles on the road by the year 2030 would be ADAS-enabled.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Major car brands with Level 2 features include Lexus, Audi, BMW, Mercedes-Benz, Tesla, Volvo, Tata, Citroën, Ford, Hyundai, Kia, Mazda, Nissan, Peugeot, Mahindra and Subaru.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Full Level 2 features are included with Full Self-Driving from Tesla, Pilot Assist from Volvo, OpenPilot from Comma.ai and ProPILOT Assist from Nissan.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Level 3 features are included in Honda Sensing Elite from Honda and Drive Pilot from Mercedes-Benz.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] SGO 2021-01 subsequently was amended on August 5, 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] SGO 2021-01 is in effect for three years, starting on June 29, 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] After gathering data for almost a year (July 1, 2021 through May 15, 2022), the NHTSA released the initial set of data in June 2022 and stated they plan to update the data on a monthly basis.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Of the 130 crashes, 108 had no associated injuries reported; there was only one serious injury associated with the remaining crashes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The most commonly-reported damage location was the rear of the ADS-equipped vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Similarly, ADAS (Level 2) from 12 different manufacturers were involved in 367 crashes over the same period; 392 crashes were reported in total, but 25 either occurred before July 2021 or had no associated date.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Reported incidents were led by Tesla (273), Honda (90), and Subaru (10).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Of the 392 crashes, 98 included injury reporting; of the 98, 46 had no injuries reported, 5 resulted in serious injuries and 6 resulted in fatalities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The most commonly-reported damage location was the front of the ADAS-equipped vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] According to PACTS, lack of full standardization may make ADAS in different cars difficult for drivers to understand.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Button names and locations, as well as dashboard symbols, change from car to car due to lack of standardization.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS might have many limitations, for instance a pre-collision system might have 12 pages to explain 23 exceptions where ADAS may operate when not needed and 30 exceptions where ADAS may not operate when a collision is likely.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Names for ADAS features are not standardized.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] For instance, adaptive cruise control is called *Adaptive Cruise Control* by Fiat, Ford, GM, VW, Volvo and Peugeot, but *Intelligent Cruise Control* by Nissan, *Active Cruise Control* by Citroen and BMW, and *DISTRONIC* by Mercedes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] To help with standardization, SAE International has endorsed a series of recommendations for generic ADAS terminology for car manufacturers, created with Consumer Reports, the American Automobile Association, J.D.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS behavior might change from car to car as well; for instanc,e ACC speed might be temporarily overridden in most cars, while some switch to standby after one minute.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The AV industry is growing exponentially, and according to a report by Market Research Future, the market is expected to hit over $65 billion by 2027.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] AV insurance and rising competition are expected to fuel that growth.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Auto insurance for ADAS has directly affected the global economy, and many questions have arisen within the general public.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS allow autonomous vehicles to enable self-driving features, but there are associated risks with ADAS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] AV companies and manufacturers are recommended to have insurance in the following areas in order to avoid any serious litigations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Depending on the level, ranging from 0 to 5, each car manufacturer would find it in its best interest to find the right combination of different insurances to best match their products.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Note that this list is not exhaustive and may be constantly updated with more types of insurances and risks in the years to come.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] With the technology embedded in autonomous vehicles, these self-driving cars are able to distribute data if a car crash occurs.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This, in turn, will invigorate the claims administration and their operations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Fraud reduction will also disable any fraudulent staging of car crashes by recording the car's monitoring of every minute on the road.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS are expected to streamline the insurance industry and its economic efficiency with capable technology to fight off fraudulent human behavior.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In September 2016, the NHTSA published the Federal Automated Vehicles Policy, which describes the U.S.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Department of Transportation's policies related to highly automated vehicles (HAV) which range from vehicles with ADAS features to autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In March 2014, the US Department of Transportation's National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) announced that it will require all new vehicles under 10,000 pounds (4,500 kg) to have rear view cameras by May 2018.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The rule was required by Congress as part of the Cameron Gulbransen Kids Transportation Safety Act of 2007.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The Act is named after two-year-old Cameron Gulbransen.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The advancement of autonomous driving is accompanied by ethical concerns.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The earliest moral issue associated with autonomous driving can be dated back to as early as the age of the trolleys.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The trolley problem is one of the most well-known ethical issues.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Before the development of autonomous vehicles, the trolley problem remains an ethical dilemma between utilitarianism and deontological ethics.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] However, as the advancement in ADAS proceeds, the trolley problem becomes an issue that needs to be addressed by the programming of self-driving cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The crashes that autonomous vehicles might face could be very similar to those depicted in the trolley problem.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Although ADAS make vehicles generally safer than only human-driven cars, crashes are unavoidable.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Many researchers have been working on ways to address the ethical concerns associated with ADAS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] For instance, the artificial intelligence approach allows computers to learn human ethics by feeding them data regarding human actions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Such a method is useful when the rules cannot be articulated because the computer can learn and identify the ethical elements on its own without precisely programming whether an action is ethical.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] However, there are limitations to this approach.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] For example, many human actions are done out of self-preservation instincts, which is realistic but not ethical; feeding such data to the computer cannot guarantee that the computer captures the ideal behavior.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Furthermore, the data fed to an artificial intelligence must be carefully selected to avoid producing undesired outcomes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Another notable method is a three-phase approach proposed by Noah J.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This approach first necessitates a system established with the agreement of car manufacturers, transportation engineers, lawyers, and ethicists, and should be set transparently.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The second phase is letting artificial intelligence learn human ethics while being bound by the system established in phase one.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Lastly, the system should provide constant feedback that is understandable by humans.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In October 2023, Consumer Reports rated 17 "active driving assistance systems".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In March 2024, the American Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS) reported its first "partial automation safeguard ratings".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Intelligent transportation systems (ITS) highly resemble ADAS, but go beyond automatic traffic to include any enterprise that safely transports humans, such as public transport.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] With ITS, transportation technology is integrated with a city's infrastructure.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems promote active safety by increasing the efficiency of roads, possibly by adding 22.5% capacity on average.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS have aided in this increase in active safety, according to a study in 2008.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ITS use a wide system of communication technology, including wireless technology and traditional technology, to enhance productivity.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] A draft ADAS regulation named *driver control assistance systems* (DCAS) would allow hands-free driving with a possible risk of lack of attentiveness.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Such DCAS regulation would allow system such as Tesla FSD in Europe.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The UNECE driver control assistance systems regulation plan that DCAS shall be designed to ensure that the driver performs the driving task, that the driver's hands must remain on the wheel and that the system shall monitor the driver's visual engagement.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Related technology includes advanced software, maps, vehicle changes, and outside vehicle support.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The benefits of viewing automated driving from a sociotechnical systems perspective has been discussed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Autonomy presents varying issues for road, air, and marine travel.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Roads present the most significant complexity given the unpredictability of the driving environment, including diverse road designs, driving conditions, traffic, obstacles, and geographical/cultural differences.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Autonomy implies that the vehicle is responsible for all perception, monitoring, and control functions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Autonomous vehicle software generally contains several different modules that work together to enable self-driving capabilities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The perception module ingests and processes data from various sensors, such cameras, LIDAR, RADAR, and ultrasonic SONAR, to create a comprehensive understanding of the vehicle's surroundings.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The localization module uses 3D point cloud data, GPS, IMU, and mapping information to determine the vehicle's precise position, including its orientation, velocity, and angular rate.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The planning module takes inputs from both perception and localization to compute actions to take, such as velocity and steering angle outputs.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] These modules are typically supported by machine learning algorithms, particularly deep neural networks, which enable the vehicle to detect objects, interpret traffic patterns, and make real-time decisions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Furthermore, modern autonomous driving systems increasingly employ sensor fusion techniques that combine data from multiple sensors to improve accuracy and reliability in different environmental conditions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The perception system is responsible for observing the environment.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] It must identify everything that could affect the trip, including other vehicles, pedestrians, cyclists, their movements, road conditions, obstacles, and other issues.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Various makers use cameras, radar, lidar, sonar, and microphones that can collaboratively minimize errors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Navigation systems are a necessary element in autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The Global Positioning System (GPS) is used for navigation by air, water, and land vehicles, particularly for off-road navigation.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] For road vehicles, two approaches are prominent.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] One is to use maps that hold data about lanes and intersections, relying on the vehicle's perception system to fill in the details.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The other is to use highly detailed maps that reduce the scope of real-time decision-making but require significant maintenance as the environment evolves.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Some systems crowdsource their map updates, using the vehicles themselves to update the map to reflect changes such as construction or traffic used by the entire vehicle fleet.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Another potential source of information is the environment itself.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Traffic data may be supplied by roadside monitoring systems and used to route vehicles to best use a limited road system.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Additionally, modern GNSS enhancement technologies, such as real-time kinematic (RTK) and precise point positioning (PPP), enhance the accuracy of vehicle positioning to sub-meter level precision, which is crucial for autonomous navigation and decision-making.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The *"Stanford Cart",* created by Hans Moravec in the late 1970s while he was a graduate student, was the first experimental autonomous vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] It was a precursor to both NASA's Moon and Mars Lander projects as it was known at the time that radio signal lag times would have made anything other than autonomous control impractical.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The box rested on 4 bicycle wheels, and had a camera, battery and a radio antenna connecting it wirelessly to a remote computer.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Morovic was able to get the Cart to navigate around large obstacles in a 100 foot long room, albeit it would take 5 hours as the cart would frequently stop as the computer processed images which it analyzed and then responded with navigation instructions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Automated vehicles in European Union legislation refer specifically to road vehicles (car, truck, or bus).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] For those vehicles, a specific difference is legally defined between advanced driver-assistance system and autonomous/automated vehicles, based on liability differences.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety tested two automatic emergency braking systems: some designed to prevent crashes and others that aim to make a crash less severe.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The test looked at popular models like the 2016 Volvo XC90, Subaru Legacy, Lincoln MKX, Honda Civic, and Volkswagen Passat.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Researchers tested how well each system stopped when approaching moving and nonmoving targets.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] It found that systems capable of preventing crashes reduced vehicle speeds by twice that of the systems designed to mitigate crash severity.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] When the two test vehicles traveled within 30 mph of each other, even those designed to lessen crash severity avoided crashes 60 percent of the time.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The SAfe Road TRains for the Environment (Sartre) project's goal was to enable platooning, in which a line of cars and trucks (a "train") follow a human-driven vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Trains were predicted to provide comfort and allow the following vehicles to travel safely to a destination.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Human drivers encountering a train could join and delegate driving to the human driver.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Self-driving Uber vehicles were tested in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The tests were paused after an autonomous car killed a woman in Arizona.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Automated busses have been tested in California.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In San Diego, California, an automated bus test used magnetic markers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The longitudinal control of automated truck platoons used millimeter wave radio and radar.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Tesla FSD allows drivers to enter a destination and let the car take over.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Ford offers Blue Cruise, technology that allows geofenced cars to drive autonomously.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Drivers are directed to stay attentive, and safety warnings are implemented to alert the driver when corrective action is needed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Tesla, Incorporated has one recorded incident that resulted in a fatality involving the automated driving system in the Tesla Model S.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The accident report reveals the accident was a result of the driver being inattentive and the autopilot system not recognizing the obstruction ahead.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Tesla has also had multiple instances where the vehicle crashed into a garage door.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] According to the book "The Driver in the Driverless Car: How Your Technology Choices Create the Future," Tesla automatically performs an update overnight.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The morning after the update, the driver used his app to "summon" his car, and it crashed into his garage door.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Another flaw with automated driving systems is that unpredictable events, such as weather or the driving behavior of others, may cause fatal accidents due to sensors that monitor the surroundings of the vehicle not being able to provide corrective action.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Implementing automated driving systems poses the possibility of changing built environments in urban areas, such as expanding the suburban regions due to the increased ease of mobility.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Around 2015, several self-driving car companies including Nissan and Toyota promised self-driving cars by 2020.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] However, the predictions turned out to be far too optimistic.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] There are still many obstacles in developing fully autonomous Level 5 vehicles, which is the ability to operate in any conditions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Currently, companies are focused on Level 4 automation, which is able to operate under certain environmental circumstances.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] There is still debate about what an autonomous vehicle should look like.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] For example, whether to incorporate lidar to autonomous driving systems is still being argued.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Some researchers have come up with algorithms using camera-only data that achieve the performance that rival those of lidar.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] On the other hand, camera-only data sometimes draw inaccurate bounding boxes, and thus lead to poor predictions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] This is due to the nature of superficial information that stereo cameras provide, whereas incorporating lidar gives autonomous vehicles precise distance to each point on the vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] These features require numerous sensors, many of which rely on micro-electro-mechanical systems (MEMS) to maintain a small size, high efficiency, and low cost.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Foremost among MEMS sensors in vehicles are accelerometers and gyroscopes to measure acceleration around multiple orthogonal axes—critical to detecting and controlling the vehicle's motion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] One critical step to achieve the implementation of autonomous vehicles is the acceptance by the general public.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] It provides guidelines for the automobile industry to improve their design and technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Studies have shown that many people believe that using autonomous vehicles is safer, which underlines the necessity for the automobile companies to assure that autonomous vehicles improve safety benefits.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The TAM research model breaks down important factors that affect the consumer's acceptance into: usefulness, ease to use, trust, and social influence.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Real-time testing of autonomous vehicles is an inevitable part of the process.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] At the same time, vehicular automation regulators are faced with challenges to protect public safety and yet allow autonomous vehicle companies to test their products.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Groups representing autonomous vehicle companies are resisting most regulations, whereas groups representing vulnerable road users and traffic safety are pushing for regulatory barriers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] To improve traffic safety, the regulators are encouraged to find a middle ground that protects the public from immature technology while allowing autonomous vehicle companies to test the implementation of their systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Regulators face daunting challenges such as jurisdictional ambiguities, the rapid obsolescence of current technologies and the lack of future-looking cost-benefit data to support regulatory development.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] There have also been proposals to adopt the aviation automation safety regulatory knowledge into the discussions of safe implementation of autonomous vehicles, due to the experience that has been gained over the decades by the aviation sector on safety topics.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In some countries, specific laws and regulations apply to road traffic motor vehicles (such as cars, bus and trucks) while other laws and regulations apply to other ground vehicles such as tram, train or automated guided vehicles making them to operate in different environments and conditions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] This amendment will enter into force on 14 July 2022, unless it is rejected before 13 January 2022.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Ground vehicles employing automation and teleoperation include shipyard gantries, mining trucks, bomb-disposal robots, robotic insects, and driverless tractors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] There are many autonomous and semi-autonomous ground vehicles being made for the purpose of transporting passengers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] One such example is the free-ranging on grid (FROG) technology which consists of autonomous vehicles, a magnetic track and a supervisory system.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The system experienced a crash in 2005 that proved to be caused by a human error.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Research is ongoing and prototypes of autonomous ground vehicles exist.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Extensive automation for cars focuses on either introducing robotic cars or modifying modern car designs to be semi-autonomous.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Semi-autonomous designs could be implemented sooner as they rely less on technology that is still at the forefront of research.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Groups such as RUF (Denmark) and TriTrack (USA) are working on projects consisting of specialized private cars that are driven manually on normal roads but also that dock onto a monorail/guideway along which they are driven autonomously.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] As a method of automating cars without extensively modifying the cars as much as a robotic car, Automated highway systems (AHS) aims to construct lanes on highways that would be equipped with, for example, magnets to guide the vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Automation vehicles have auto-brakes named as Auto Vehicles Braking System (AVBS).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Highway computers would manage the traffic and direct the cars to avoid crashes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In 2006, The European Commission has established a smart car development program called the *Intelligent Car Flagship Initiative*.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] There are further uses for automation in relation to cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Singapore also announced a set of provisional national standards on January 31, 2019, to guide the autonomous vehicle industry.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Since 1999, the 12-seat/10-standing ParkShuttle has been operating on an 1.8 kilometres (1.1 mi) exclusive right of way in the city of Capelle aan den IJssel in The Netherlands.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The system uses small magnets in the road surface to allow the vehicle to determine its position.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The use of shared autonomous vehicles was trialed around 2012 in a hospital car park in Portugal.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] From 2012 to 2016, the European Union funded CityMobil2 project examined the use of shared autonomous vehicles and passenger experience including short term trials in seven cities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] This project led to the development of the EasyMile EZ10.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In the 2010s, self-driving shuttle became able to run in mixed traffic without the need for embedded guidance markers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] So far the focus has been on low speed, 20 miles per hour (32 km/h), with short, fixed routes for the "last mile" of journeys.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] This means issues of collision avoidance and safety are significantly less challenging than those for automated cars, which seek to match the performance of conventional vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Many trials have been undertaken, mainly on quiet roads with little traffic or on public pathways or private roadways and specialised test sites.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The capacity of different models varies significantly, between 6-seats and 20-seats.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In December 2016, the Jacksonville Transportation Authority has announced its intention to replace the Jacksonville Skyway monorail with driverless vehicles that would run on the existing elevated superstructure as well as continue onto ordinary roads.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The project has since been named the "Ultimate Urban Circulator" or "U2C" and testing has been carried out on shuttles from six different manufacturers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The cost of the project is estimated at $379 million.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In January 2017, it was announced the ParkShuttle system in the Netherlands will be renewed and expanded including extending the route network beyond the exclusive right of way so vehicles will run in mixed traffic on ordinary roads.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The plans were delayed and the extension into mixed traffic was expected in 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In July 2018, Baidu stated it had built 100 of its 8-seat Apolong model, with plans for commercial sales.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] As of July 2021, they had not gone into volume production.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In August 2020, it was reported there were 25 autonomous shuttle manufacturers, including the 2GetThere, Local Motors, Navya, Baidu, Easymile, Toyota and Ohmio.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In December 2020, Toyota showcased its 20-passenger "e-Palette" vehicle, which is due to be used at the 2021 Tokyo Olympic Games.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Toyota announced it intends to have the vehicle available for commercial applications before 2025.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In January 2021, Navya released an investor report which predicted global autonomous shuttle sales will reach 12,600 units by 2025, with a market value of EUR 1.7 billion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In June 2021, Chinese maker Yutong claimed to have delivered 100 models of its 10-seat Xiaoyu 2.0 autonomous bus for use in Zhengzhou.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Testing has been carried out in a number of cities since 2019 with trials open to the public planned for July 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Self-driving shuttles are already in use on some private roads, such as at the Yutong factory in Zhengzhou where they are used to transport workers between buildings of the world's largest bus factory.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In Hong Kong, the police and other workers use driverless vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] A large number of trials have been conducted since 2016, with most involving only one vehicle on a short route for a short period of time and with an onboard conductor.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The purpose of the trials has been to both provide technical data and to familiarize the public with the driverless technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] A 2021 survey of over 100 shuttle experiments across Europe concluded that low speed – 15–20 kilometres per hour (9.3–12.4 mph) – was the major barrier to implementation of autonomous shuttle buses.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The current cost of the vehicles at €280,000 and the need for onboard attendants were also issues.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Autonomous buses are proposed, as well as self-driving cars and trucks.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Grade 2 level automated minibusses were trialed for a few weeks in Stockholm.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] China has a small fleet of self-driving public buses in the tech district of Shenzhen, Guangdong.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Passenger-carrying driverless bus trials in Scotland commenced in January 2023, with a fleet of five identical vehicles to the Manchester trial used on a 14 miles (23 km) Stagecoach Fife park-and-ride route across the Forth Road Bridge, from the north bank of the Forth to Edinburgh Park station.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The trial route will be extended to Didcot Parkway railway station after acquiring a larger single-decker by the end of 2023.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In October 2023, Imagry, an Israeli AI startup, introduced its mapless autonomous driving solution at Busworld Europe, leveraging a real-time image recognition system and a spatial deep convolutional neural network (DCNN) to mimic human driving behavior.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In September 2025, trade publications described the "smartbus" concept in connection with depot-based autonomous bus operation for manoeuvres such as parking, washing, and charging, in coverage of Autonomous Systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The concept was presented at Busworld Europe later that year.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In December 2025, a smartbus pilot involving the public transport operator PKM Gliwice in Poland was reported.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Modular autonomous transit is a research concept for public transit using self-driving vehicles with connectable units, or "pods", that can adjust capacity based on passenger demand.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Studies suggest these systems could improve efficiency through dynamic routing, with simulations showing reduced travel times in urban networks, though no operational systems existed as of 2025.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The concept for autonomous vehicles has been applied for commercial uses, such as autonomous or nearly autonomous trucks.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Companies such as Suncor Energy, a Canadian energy company, and Rio Tinto Group were among the first to replace human-operated trucks with driverless commercial trucks run by computers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In April 2016, trucks from major manufacturers including Volvo and the Daimler Company completed a week of autonomous driving across Europe, organized by the Dutch, in an effort to get self-driving trucks on the road.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] With developments in self-driving trucks progressing, U.S. self-driving truck sales is expected to reach 60,000 by 2035 according to a report released by IHS Incorporated in June 2016.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] As reported in June 1995 in *Popular Science* magazine, self-driving trucks were being developed for combat convoys, whereby only the lead truck would be driven by a human and the following trucks would rely on satellite, an inertial guidance system and ground-speed sensors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Caterpillar Incorporated made early developments in 2013 with the Robotics Institute at Carnegie Mellon University to improve efficiency and reduce cost at various mining and construction sites.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In Europe, the Safe Road Trains for the Environment is such an approach.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] From PWC's Strategy & Report, self driving trucks will be the source of concern around how this technology will impact around 3 million truck drivers in the US, as well as 4 million employees in support of the trucking economy in gas stations, restaurants, bars and hotels.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] At the same time, some companies like Starsky, are aiming for Level 3 Autonomy, which would see the driver playing a control role around the truck's environment.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The company's project, remote truck driving, would give truck drivers a greater work-life balance, enabling them to avoid long periods away from their home.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] This would however provoke a potential mismatch between the driver's skills with the technological redefinition of the job.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Companies that buy driverless trucks could massively cut costs: human drivers would no longer be required, companies' liabilities due to truck accidents would diminish, and productivity would increase (as the driverless truck doesn't need to rest).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The usage of self driving trucks will go hand in hand with the use of real-time data to optimize both efficiency and productivity of the service delivered, as a way to tackle traffic congestion for example.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Driverless trucks could enable new business models that would see deliveries shift from day time to night time or time slots in which traffic is less heavily dense.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Several self-balancing autonomous motorcycles were demonstrated in 2017 and 2018 from BMW, Honda and Yamaha.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The concept for autonomous vehicles has also been applied for commercial uses, like for autonomous trains.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The world's first driverless urban transit system is the Port Island Line in Kobe, Japan, opened in 1981.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] The first self-driving train in the UK was launched in London on the Thameslink route.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] An example of an automated train network is the Docklands Light Railway in London.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Also see List of automated train systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] In 2018 the first autonomous trams in Potsdam were trialed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] An automated guided vehicle or automatic guided vehicle (AGV) is a mobile robot that follows markers or wires in the floor, or uses vision, magnets, or lasers for navigation.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] They are most often used in industrial applications to move materials around a manufacturing facility or warehouse.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p01] Application of the automatic guided vehicle had broadened during the late 20th century.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Aircraft have received much attention for automation, especially for navigation.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] A system capable of autonomously navigating a vehicle (especially aircraft) is known as autopilot.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Various industries such as packages and food have experimented with delivery drones.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Traditional and new transportation companies are competing in the market.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] For example, UPS Flight Forward, Alphabet Wing, and Amazon Prime Air are all developing delivery drones.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Zipline, an American medical drone delivery company, has the largest active drone delivery operations in the world, and its drones are capable of Level 4 autonomy.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] This process is in different phases across the world as each country will tackle the topic independently.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] For example, Iceland's government and departments of transport, aviation, police have already started issuing licenses for drone operations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] It has a permissive approach and together with Costa Rica, Italy, the UAE, Sweden and Norway, has a fairly unrestricted legislation on commercial drone use.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Those countries are characterized by a body of regulation that may give operational guidelines or require licensing, registration and insurance.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] On the other side, other countries have decided to ban, either directly (outright ban) or indirectly (effective ban), the use of commercial drones.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] The RAND Corporation thus notes the difference between countries forbidding drones and those that have a formal process for commercial drone licensing, but requirements are either impossible to meet or licenses do not appear to have been approved.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] In the US, United Parcel Service is the only delivery service with the Part 135 Standard certification that is required to use drones to deliver to real customers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] However, most countries seem to be struggling on the integration of drones for commercial uses into their aviation regulatory frameworks.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Thus, constraints are placed on the use of those drones such as that they must be operating within the visual line of sight (VLOS) of the pilot and thus limiting their potential range.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] This would be the case of the Netherlands and Belgium.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Most countries let pilots operate outside the VLOS but is subject to restrictions and pilot ratings, which would be the case of the US.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] The general trend is that legislation is moving fast and laws are constantly being reevaluated.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Countries are moving towards a more permissive approach but the industry still lacks infrastructures to ensure the success of such a transition.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] To provide safety and efficiency, specialized training courses, pilot exams (type of UAV and flying conditions) as well as liability management measures regarding insurances may need to be developed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] There is a sense of urgency related to this innovation as competition is high and companies lobby to integrate them rapidly in their products and services offerings.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Since June 2017, the US Senate legislation reauthorized the Federal Aviation Administration and the Department of Transportation to create a carrier certificate allowing for package deliveries by drones.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Autonomous boats can provide security, perform research, or conduct hazardous or repetitive tasks (such as guiding a large ship into a harbor or transporting cargo).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Sea Hunter is an autonomous unmanned surface vehicle (USV) launched in 2016 as part of the DARPA Anti-Submarine Warfare Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) program.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Underwater vehicles have been a focus for automation for tasks such as pipeline inspection and underwater mapping.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] This four-legged robot was created to be able to navigate through many different terrain outdoors and indoors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] It can walk on its own without colliding into anything.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] It uses many different sensors, including 360-degree vision cameras and gyroscopes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] It is able to keep its balance even when pushed over.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] This vehicle, while it is not intended to be ridden, can carry heavy loads for construction workers or military personnel through rough terrain.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Through the autonomy level, it is shown that the higher the level of autonomy, the less control humans have on their vehicles (highest level of autonomy needing zero human interventions).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] One concerns regarding the development of vehicular automation is related to the end-users' trust in the technology that controls automated vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] According to a nationally conducted survey made by Kelley Blue Book (KBB) in 2016, it was shown that the majority of people would choose to have a certain level of control behind their own vehicle rather than having the vehicle operate in Level 5 autonomy, or in other words, complete autonomy.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] According to half of the respondents, the idea of safety in an autonomous vehicle diminishes as the level of autonomy increases.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] This distrust of autonomous driving systems proved to be unchanged throughout the years when a nationwide survey conducted by AAA Foundation for Traffic and Safety (AAAFTS) in 2019 showed the same outcome as the survey KBB did in 2016.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] AAAFTS survey showed that even though people have a certain level of trust in automated vehicles, most people also have doubts and distrust towards the technology used in autonomous vehicles, with most distrust in Level 5 autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] It is shown by AAAFTS' survey that people's trust in autonomous driving systems increased when their level of understanding increased.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] The possibility of autonomous vehicle's technology to experience malfunctions is also one of the causes of user's distrust in autonomous driving systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] It is the concern that most respondents voted for in the AAAFTS survey.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Even though autonomous vehicles are made to improve traffic safety by minimizing crashes and their severity, they still caused fatalities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] At least 113 autonomous vehicle related accidents have occurred until 2018.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] In 2015, Google declared that their automated vehicles experienced at least 272 failures, and drivers had to intervene around 13 times to prevent fatalities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Furthermore, other automated vehicles' manufacturers also reported automated vehicles' failures, including the Uber car incident.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] A self-driving Uber car accident in 2018 is an example of autonomous vehicle accidents that are also listed among self-driving car fatalities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] A report made by the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) showed that the self-driving Uber car was unable to identify the victim in a sufficient amount of time for the vehicle to slow down and avoid crashing into the victim.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Another concern related to vehicle automation is its ethical issues.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] In reality, autonomous vehicles can encounter inevitable traffic accidents.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] In such situations, many risks and calculations need to be made in order to minimize the amount of damage the accident could cause.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] When a human driver encounters an inevitable accident, the driver will take a spontaneous action based on ethical and moral logic.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] However, when a driver has no control over the vehicle (Level 5 autonomy), the system of an autonomous vehicle needs to make that quick decision.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Unlike humans, autonomous vehicles can only make decisions based on what it is programmed to do.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] However, the situation and circumstances of accidents differ from one another, and any one decision might not be the best decision for certain accidents.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Based on two research studies in 2019, the implementation of fully automated vehicles in traffic where semi-automated and non-automated vehicles are still present might lead to complications.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Some flaws that still need consideration include the structure of liability, distribution of responsibilities, efficiency in decision making, and the performance of autonomous vehicles with its diverse surroundings.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Still, researchers Steven Umbrello and Roman V.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/automated-driving-system-p02] Yampolskiy propose that the value sensitive design approach is one method that can be used to design autonomous vehicles to avoid some of these ethical issues and design for human values.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A **self-driving car**, also known as an **autonomous car**, **driverless car**, **robotic car**, or **robo-car**, is a car that is capable of operating with reduced or no human input.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] They are sometimes called **robotaxis**, though this term refers specifically to self-driving cars operated for a ridesharing company.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] As of 2026, the term "self-driving" lacks an agreed standard definition and is also subject to commercial advertising and branding considerations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Following a history of experimentation and development of advanced driver assistance systems (ADAS) after World War II, two main technologies are now primarily used: LiDAR (Light Detection and Ranging), and visual sensors (cameras) which capture images and video like human eyes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] These are combined with systems such as Global Positioning System (GPS), neural networks, artificial intelligence, and established ADAS engineering to deliver LeJs of driving autonomy.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The primary obstacle to self-driving is the advanced software and mapping required to make them work safely across the wide variety of conditions that drivers experience.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] However, the software is not yet advanced enough to handle all circumstances and has caused accidents and deaths.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Other issues include security of over-the-air updates, legal and regulatory issues, ethics, and consumer confidence.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Methods of testing and monitoring the reliability of cars have evolved in parallel with deployment, with various standards being proposed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Implications for urban infrastructure and the economy have also been discussed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Public perception and acceptance of autonomous cars has been mixed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A survey in 2022 found only 27% of the world's population would feel safe in one.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Public acceptance is also influenced by "self-AV bias", where drivers judge identical autonomous vehicle driving much more harshly than human.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Self-driving cars were anticipated by experiments in radio control during the 1920s, and the development of advanced driver assistance (ADAS) after WWII.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Trials of self-driving vehicles began in the 1950s with the first semi-autonomous car developed in 1977 by Japan's Tsukuba Mechanical Engineering Laboratory.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In the United States, Carnegie Mellon University's Navlab began semi-autonomous vehicle projects in 1984, funded by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In Europe, similar projects were led by Mercedes-Benz and the University of the Bundeswehr Munich's EUREKA Prometheus Project, beginning in 1987.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The United States allocated US$650 million in 1991 for research on the National Automated Highway System, which demonstrated automated driving combining highway-embedded automation with vehicle technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Until the second DARPA Grand Challenge in 2005, automated vehicle research in the United States was primarily funded by DARPA, the US Army and the US Navy, producing incremental advances in speed, driving competence, control, and sensor systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Since then, numerous private companies and both private and public research organizations around the world have developed working autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2015, the Cruise subsidiary of General Motors began road testing in California.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Two years later, Waymo was the first to commercialize a robotaxi service in Phoenix, Arizona, followed by a similar service by DeepRoute.ai in Shenzhen.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Cruise later shut down in 2024, with several other manufacturers scaling back plans for self-driving technology in 2022, including Ford and Volkswagen due to misgivings about commercial viability.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Legal and regulatory developments to accommodate the testing and facilitation of self-driving vehicles have also taken place worldwide.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In the 2010s and 2020s, some UNECE and EU members developed rules and regulations related to automated vehicles, with various cities planning to operate transport systems for driverless cars and to allow testing of robotic cars in traffic.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] From the 2010s, increasingly rapid progress in research and development has taken place, often accompanied by inaccurate predictions of complete autonomy, which capability is so far confined to driverless taxi services in designated cities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] As of early 2024, several manufacturers sell cars with automated driving systems in the US, Japan, Europe, and China.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Organizations such as the global standards body SAE International (SAE) have proposed terminology to describe technical capabilities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] However, most terms have no standard definition and are employed variously by vendors and others.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Proposals to adopt aviation automation terminology for cars has also not prevailed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The first consideration is the operational design domain (ODD).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The concept presumes that automated systems have limitations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Relating system function to the ODD it supports is important for developers and regulators to establish and communicate safe operating conditions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Systems should operate within those limitations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Some systems recognize the ODD and modify their behavior accordingly.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] For example, an autonomous car might recognize that traffic is heavy and disable its automated lane change feature.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Vendors have taken a variety of approaches to the self-driving problem.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Tesla's approach is to allow their "full self-driving" (FSD) system to be used in all ODDs as a Level 2 (hands/on, eyes/on) ADAS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Waymo picked specific ODDs (city streets in Phoenix and San Francisco) for their Level 5 robotaxi service.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Mercedes Benz offers Level 3 service in Las Vegas in highway traffic jams at speeds up to 40 miles per hour (64 km/h).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Mobileye's SuperVision system offers hands-off/eyes-on driving on all road types at speeds up to 130 km/h (81 mph).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] GM's hands-free Super Cruise operates on specific roads in specific conditions, stopping or returning control to the driver when ODD changes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2024 the company announced plans to expand road coverage from 400,000 miles to 750,000 miles (1,210,000 km).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Ford's BlueCruise hands-off system operates on 130,000 miles (210,000 km) of US divided highways.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Names such as AutonoDrive, PilotAssist, "Full-Self Driving" or DrivePilot are used even though the products offer an assortment of features that may not match the names.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Despite offering a system dubbed Full Self-Driving, Tesla stated that its system did not autonomously handle all driving tasks.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In the United Kingdom, a fully self-driving car is defined as a car so registered, rather than one that supports a specific feature set.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The Association of British Insurers claimed that the usage of the word *autonomous* in marketing was dangerous because car ads make motorists think "autonomous" and "autopilot" imply that the driver can rely on the car to control itself, even though they do not.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The following are useful in understanding the various definitions and criteria in use for self-driving cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Advanced driver-assistance systems (ADAS) automate specific driving features such as Forward Collision Warning (FCW), Automatic Emergency Braking (AEB), Lane Departure Warning (LDW), Lane Keeping Assistance (LKA) or Blind Spot Warning (BSW).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] An ADAS requires a human driver to handle tasks that the ADAS does not support.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ADAS contrasts to an automated driving system (ADS), which would be classified by SAE J3016 as Level 3 or higher.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Autonomy implies that an automation system is under the control of the vehicle rather than a driver.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Automation is function-specific, handling issues such as speed control, but leaves broader decision-making to the driver.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The European car safety performance assessment programme Euro NCAP defines "autonomous" as "the system acts independently of the driver to avoid or mitigate the accident".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In Europe, the words *automated* and *autonomous* can be used together.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A remote driver is a driver that operates a vehicle at a distance, using a video and data connection.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The Union of Concerned Scientists defined self-driving as "cars or trucks in which human drivers are never required to take control to safely operate the vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The British Automated and Electric Vehicles Act 2018 defines a vehicle as "driving itself" if the vehicle is "not being controlled, and does not need to be monitored, by an individual".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Another British government definition stated, "Self-driving vehicles are vehicles that can safely and lawfully drive themselves".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The first occurrence of the "automated" word refers to a UNECE automated system, while the second refers to the British legal definition of an automated vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] British law interprets the meaning of "automated vehicle" based on the interpretation section related to a vehicle "driving itself" and an insured vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In November 2023 the British Government introduced the Automated Vehicles Bill.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The system was adopted by the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UNECE) in the form of UN Regulation No.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] 157, which came into force in January 2021, and used in over 50 countries.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] After SAE updated its classification in 2016, (J3016_201609), the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) adopted the SAE standard.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The classification is a topic of debate, having been criticized for its technological focus, with various revisions proposed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] It has been argued that the structure of the levels suggests that automation increases linearly and that more automation is better, which may not be the case.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] SAE levels also do not account for changes that may be required to infrastructure and road user behavior.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Cars may therefore switch levels according to the driving mode.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A human analogy might be a mode in which you can stand unassisted on one leg (the requirement) if you are on the ground (the ODD), but would need support when standing on a tightrope.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Above Level 1, level differences are related to how responsibility for safe movement is divided/shared between the advanced driver-assistance system (ADAS) and driver, rather than specific driving features (see Concepts).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A car might therefore have Level 3 capability for lane management (the driving requirement) up to 100 km/h (the ODD), but Level 2 at speeds faster than that.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Or it might have Level 4 for driverless navigation on designated highways, but Level 2 on urban side roads.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ADASs that are considered Level 1 are adaptive cruise control, emergency brake assist, automatic emergency brake assist, lane-keeping, and lane centering.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ADASs that are considered Level 2 are highway assist, autonomous obstacle avoidance, and autonomous parking.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] At Level 3 and above, if a car is driving and the ODD changes—for instance, a clear highway becomes a construction zone with hand-signals from a worker—the system must recognize that it is exiting its ODD and fall back accordingly, including asking for driver intervention if necessary.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Mobileye CEO Amnon Shashua and CTO Shai Shalev-Shwartz proposed an alternative taxonomy for autonomous driving systems, claiming that a more consumer-friendly approach was needed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Its categories reflect the amount of driver engagement that is required.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Some vehicle makers have informally adopted some of the terminology involved, while not formally committing to it.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The first level, hands-on/eyes-on, implies that the driver is fully engaged in operating the vehicle, but is supervised by the system, which intervenes according to the features it supports (e.g., adaptive cruise control, automatic emergency braking).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The driver is entirely responsible, with hands on the wheel and eyes on the road.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Eyes-on/hands-off allows the driver to let go of the wheel.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The system drives, the driver monitors, and remains prepared to resume control as needed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Eyes-off/hands-off means that the driver can stop monitoring the system, leaving the system in full control.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Eyes-off requires that no errors be reproducible (not triggered by exotic transitory conditions) or frequent, that speeds are contextually appropriate (e.g., 80 mph (130 km/h) on limited-access roads), and that the system handles typical maneuvers (e.g., getting cut off by another vehicle).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The automation level could vary according to the road (e.g., eyes-off on freeways, eyes-on on side streets).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The highest level does not require a human driver in the car: monitoring is done either remotely (telepresence) or not at all.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A critical requirement for the higher two levels is that the vehicle be able to conduct a Minimum Risk Maneuver and stop safely out of traffic without driver intervention.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The perception system processes visual and audio data from outside and inside the car to create a local model of the vehicle, the road, traffic, traffic controls and other observable objects, and their relative motion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The control system then takes actions to move the vehicle, considering the local model, road map, and driving regulations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Educational robotics modules, such as the NSDL-hosted "Thinking Robotics" activity, show how foundational decision-making and sensor-based navigation concepts are used in autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Several classifications have been proposed to describe ADAS technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] One proposal is to adopt these categories: navigation, path planning, perception, and car control.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Vendors such as Tesla and Motional have opted for monolithic "end to end" (E2E) neural networks, moving away from modular systems that separate perception from control.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Navigation involves the use of maps to define a path between origin and destination.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Hybrid navigation is the use of multiple navigation systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Some systems use basic maps, relying on perception to deal with anomalies.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Such a map understands which roads lead to which others, whether a road is a freeway, a highway, are one-way, etc.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Other systems require highly detailed maps, including lane maps, obstacles, traffic controls, etc.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ACs need to be able to perceive the world around them.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Supporting technologies include combinations of cameras, LiDAR, radar, audio, and ultrasound, GPS, and inertial measurement.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Deep neural networks are used to analyse inputs from these sensors to detect and identify objects and their trajectories.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Some systems use Bayesian simultaneous localization and mapping (SLAM) algorithms.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Another technique is detection and tracking of other moving objects (DATMO), used to handle potential obstacles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Other systems use roadside real-time locating system (RTLS) technologies to aid localization.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Tesla's "vision only" system uses eight cameras, without LIDAR or radar, to create its bird's-eye view of the environment.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Path planning finds a sequence of segments that a vehicle can use to move from origin to destination.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Techniques used for path planning include graph-based search and variational-based optimization techniques.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Graph-based techniques can make harder decisions such as how to pass another vehicle/obstacle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Variational-based optimization techniques require more stringent restrictions on the vehicle's path to prevent collisions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The large scale path of the vehicle can be determined by using a voronoi diagram, an occupancy grid mapping, or a driving corridor algorithm.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The latter allows the vehicle to locate and drive within open space that is bounded by lanes or barriers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Map sophistication varies from simple graphs that show which roads connect to each other, with details such as one-way vs two-way, to those that are highly detailed, with information about lanes, traffic controls, roadworks, and more.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Researchers at the MITComputer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory (CSAIL) developed a system called MapLite, which allows self-driving cars to drive with simple maps.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The system combines the GPS position of the vehicle, a "sparse topological map" such as OpenStreetMap (which has only 2D road features), with sensors that observe road conditions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] One issue with highly detailed maps is updating them as the world changes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Vehicles that can operate with less-detailed maps do not require frequent updates or geo-fencing.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Sensors are necessary for the vehicle to properly respond to the driving environment.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Sensor types include cameras, LiDAR, ultrasound, and radar.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Control systems typically combine data from multiple sensors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Multiple sensors can provide a more complete view of the surroundings and can be used to cross-check each other to correct errors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] For example, radar can image a scene in, e.g., a nighttime snowstorm, that defeats cameras and LiDAR, albeit at reduced precision.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] After experimenting with radar and ultrasound, Tesla adopted a vision-only approach, asserting that humans drive using only vision, and that cars should be able to do the same, while citing the lower cost of cameras versus other sensor types.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] By contrast, Waymo makes use of the higher resolution of LiDAR sensors and cites the declining cost of that technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Drive by wire is the use of electrical or electro-mechanical systems for performing vehicle functions such as steering or speed control that are traditionally achieved by mechanical linkages.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Driver monitoring is used to assess the driver's attention and alertness.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Techniques in use include eye monitoring, and requiring the driver to maintain torque on the steering wheel.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] It attempts to understand driver status and identify dangerous driving behaviors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Vehicles can potentially benefit from communicating with others to share information about traffic, road obstacles, to receive map and software updates, etc.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ISO/TC 22 specifies in-vehicle transport information and control systems, while ISO/TC 204 specifies information, communication and control systems in surface transport.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] International standards have been developed for ADAS functions, connectivity, human interaction, in-vehicle systems, management/engineering, dynamic map and positioning, privacy and security.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Rather than communicating among vehicles, they can communicate with road-based systems to receive similar information.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Software controls the vehicle, and can provide entertainment and other services.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Over-the-air updates can deliver bug fixes and additional features over the internet.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Software updates are one way to accomplish recalls that in the past required a visit to a service center.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In March 2021, the UNECE regulation on software update and software update management systems was published.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A safety model is software that attempts to formalize rules that ensure that ACs operate safely.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] IEEE is attempting to forge a standard for safety models as "IEEE P2846: A Formal Model for Safety Considerations in Automated Vehicle Decision Making".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2022, a research group at National Institute of Informatics (NII, Japan) enhanced Mobileye's Reliable Safety System as "Goal-Aware RSS" to enable RSS rules to deal with complex scenarios via program logic.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In accordance with the proposed SAE J3134 "ADS Marker Lamps" specification, the US has standardized the use of turquoise lights to inform other drivers that a vehicle is driving autonomously.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] It will be used in the 2026 Mercedes-Benz EQS and S-Class sedans with Drive Pilot, an SAE Level 3 driving system.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] As of 2023, the turquoise light had not been standardized in China or by the UNECE.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Artificial intelligence (AI) plays a pivotal role in the development and operation of autonomous vehicles (AVs), enabling them to perceive their surroundings, make decisions, and navigate safely without human intervention.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] AI algorithms empower AVs to interpret sensory data from various onboard sensors, such as cameras, LiDAR, radar, and GPS, to understand their environment and improve its technological ability and overall safety over time.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The primary obstacle to ACs is the advanced software and mapping required to make them work safely across the wide variety of conditions that drivers experience.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Experimental studies show that trust in autonomous vehicles drops sharply after system failures, especially in control‑related scenarios.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Other obstacles include cost, liability, consumer reluctance, ethical dilemmas, security, privacy, and legal/regulatory framework.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Further, AVs could automate the work of professional drivers, eliminating many jobs, which could slow acceptance.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Tesla calls its Level 2 ADAS "Full Self-Driving (FSD) Beta".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] US Senators Richard Blumenthal and Edward Markey called on the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) to investigate this marketing in 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In December 2021 in Japan, Mercedes-Benz was punished by the Consumer Affairs Agency for misleading product descriptions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Mercedes-Benz was criticized for a misleading US commercial advertising E-Class models.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] At that time, Mercedes-Benz rejected the claims and stopped its "self-driving car" ad campaign that had been running.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In August 2022, the California Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) accused Tesla of deceptive marketing practices.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] With the Automated Vehicles Bill (AVB) self-driving car-makers could face prison for misleading adverts in the United-Kingdom.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In the 2020s, concerns over ACs' vulnerability to cyberattacks and data theft emerged.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2018 and 2019, former Apple engineers were charged with stealing information related to Apple's self-driving car project.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2021 the United States Department of Justice (DOJ) accused Chinese security officials of coordinating a hacking campaign to steal information from government entities, including research related to autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] China has prepared "the Provisions on Management of Automotive Data Security (Trial) to protect its own data".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Cellular Vehicle-to-Everything technologies are based on 5G wireless networks.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] As of November 2022, the US Congress was considering the possibility that imported Chinese AC technology could facilitate espionage.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Testing of Chinese automated cars in the US has raised concern over which US data are collected by Chinese vehicles to be stored in China and any link with the Chinese communist party.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ACs complicate the need for drivers to communicate with each other, e.g., to decide which car enters an intersection first.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In an AC without a driver, traditional means such as hand signals do not work (no driver, no hands).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ACs must be able to predict the behavior of possibly moving vehicles, pedestrians, etc, in real time in order to proceed safely.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The task becomes more challenging the further into the future the prediction extends, requiring rapid revisions to the estimate to cope with unpredicted behavior.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] One approach is to wholly recompute the position and trajectory of each object many times per second.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Another is to cache the results of an earlier prediction for use in the next one to reduce computational complexity.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The ADAS has to be able to safely accept control from and return control to the driver.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Consumers will avoid ACs unless they trust them as safe.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Robotaxis operating in San Francisco received pushback over perceived safety risks.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Automatic elevators were invented in 1900, but did not become common until operator strikes and trust was built with advertising and features such as an emergency stop button.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] However, with repeated use of autonomous driving functions, drivers' behavior and trust in autonomous vehicles gradually improved and both entered a more stable state.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] At the same time, this also improved the performance and reliability of the vehicle in complex conditions, thereby increasing public trust.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Autonomy also presents various political and economic implications.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The transportation sector holds significant sway in many political and economic landscapes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] For instance, many US states generate much annual revenue from transportation fees and taxes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The advent of self-driving cars could profoundly affect the economy by potentially altering state tax revenue streams.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Furthermore, the transition to autonomous vehicles might disrupt employment patterns and labor markets, particularly in industries heavily reliant on driving professions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Data from the US Bureau of Labor Statistics indicates that in 2019, the sector employed over two million individuals as tractor-trailer truck drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Additionally, taxi and delivery drivers represented approximately 370,400 positions, and bus drivers constituted a workforce of over 680,000.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Collectively, this amounts to a conceivable displacement of nearly 2.9 million jobs, surpassing the job losses experienced in the 2008 Great Recession.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The prominence of certain demographic groups within the tech industry inevitably shapes the trajectory of autonomous vehicle (AV) development, potentially perpetuating existing inequalities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2019, research from Georgia Tech revealed that autonomous vehicle detection systems were generally five percent less effective at recognizing darker-skinned individuals.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] This accuracy gap persisted despite adjustments for environmental variables like lighting and visual obstructions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Standards for liability have yet to be adopted to address crashes and other incidents.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Liability could rest with the vehicle occupant, its owner, the vehicle manufacturer, or even the ADAS technology supplier, possibly depending on the circumstances of the crash.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Additionally, the infusion of ArtificiaI Intelligence technology in autonomous vehicles adds layers of complexity to ownership and ethical dynamics.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Given that AI systems are inherently self-learning, a question arises of whether accountability should rest with the vehicle owner, the manufacturer, or the AI developer.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The trolley problem is a thought experiment in ethics.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Adapted for ACs, it considers an AC carrying one passenger confronting a pedestrian who steps in its way.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The ADAS notionally has to choose between killing the pedestrian or swerving into a wall, killing the passenger.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Possible frameworks include deontology (formal rules) and utilitarianism (harm reduction).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] One public opinion survey reported that harm reduction was preferred, except that passengers wanted the vehicle to prefer them, while pedestrians took the opposite view.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Additionally, cultural viewpoints exert substantial influence on shaping responses to these ethical quandaries.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Another study found that cultural biases impact preferences in prioritizing the rescue of certain individuals over others in car accident scenarios.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Some ACs require an internet connection to function, opening the possibility that a hacker might gain access to private information such as destinations, routes, camera recordings, media preferences, and/or behavioral patterns, although this is true of any internet-connected device.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ACs make use of road infrastructure (e.g., traffic signs, turn lanes) and may require modifications to that infrastructure to fully achieve their safety and other goals.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In March 2023, the Japanese government unveiled a plan to set up a dedicated highway lane for ACs.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In April 2023, JR East announced their challenge to raise their self-driving level of Kesennuma Line bus rapid transit (BRT) in rural area from the current Level 2 to Level 4 at 60 km/h (37 mph).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] ACs can be tested via digital simulations, in a controlled test environment, and/or on public roads.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Road testing typically requires some form of permit or a commitment to adhere to acceptable operating principles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] For example, New York requires a test driver to be in the vehicle, prepared to override the ADAS as necessary.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In California, self-driving car manufacturers are required to submit annual reports describing how often their vehicles autonomously disengaged from autonomous mode.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] This is one measure of system robustness (ideally, the system should never disengage).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Reporting companies use varying definitions of what qualifies as a disengagement, and such definitions can change over time.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Executives of self-driving car companies have criticized disengagements as a deceptive metric, because it does not consider varying road conditions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In April 2021, WP.29 GRVA proposed a "Test Method for Automated Driving (NATM)".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In October 2021, Europe's pilot test, L3Pilot, demonstrated ADAS for cars in Hamburg, Germany, in conjunction with ITS World Congress 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] SAE Level 3 and 4 functions were tested on ordinary roads.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In November 2022, an International Standard ISO 34502 on "Scenario based safety evaluation framework" was published.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In April 2022, collision avoidance testing was demonstrated by Nissan.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Waymo published a document about collision avoidance testing in December 2022.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In September 2022, Biprogy released Driving Intelligence Validation Platform (DIVP) as part of Japanese national project "SIP-adus", which is interoperable with Open Simulation Interface (OSI) of ASAM.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In November 2022, Toyota demonstrated one of its GR Yaris test cars, which had been trained using professional rally drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Toyota used its collaboration with Microsoft in FIA World Rally Championship since the 2017 season.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Large, senior research fellow with the Human Factors Research Group at the University of Nottingham, disguised himself as a car seat in a study to test people's reactions to driverless cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A meta-analysis published in Nature Communications in 2024 compared various sources of safety data for autonomous (AV) and human-driven vehicles (HDV).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] This collected 2,100 AV and 35,133 HDV incident records which accurately reflected the incident details.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Some AVs in the comparisons (such as robotaxis) were effectively autonomous, while others were equipped with Advanced Driving Systems (ADS) or Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The study concluded that AVs are safer in most circumstances, and much safer for pedestrians.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] However, the comparison found disparities: while AVs were found to be significantly less likely to crash in heavy rain or fog than an unassisted human, they were five times more vulnerable to collisions at dawn and dusk.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] As of 2023, Tesla's ADAS Autopilot/Full Self Driving (beta) was classified as Level 2 ADAS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] On 20 January 2016, the first of five known fatal crashes of a Tesla with Autopilot occurred, in China's Hubei province.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Initially, Tesla stated that the vehicle was so badly damaged from the impact that their recorder was not able to determine whether the car had been on Autopilot at the time.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] However, the car failed to take evasive action.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Another fatal Autopilot crash occurred in May in Florida in a Tesla Model S that crashed into a tractor-trailer.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In a civil suit between the father of the driver killed and Tesla, Tesla documented that the car had been on Autopilot.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] According to Tesla, "neither Autopilot nor the driver noticed the white side of the tractor-trailer against a brightly lit sky, so the brake was not applied." Tesla claimed that this was Tesla's first known Autopilot death in over 130 million miles (210 million kilometers) with Autopilot engaged.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Tesla claimed that on average one fatality occurs every 94 million miles (151 million kilometers) across all vehicle types in the US.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] However, this number also includes motorcycle/pedestrian fatalities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The ultimate National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) report concluded Tesla was not at fault; the investigation revealed that for Tesla cars, the crash rate dropped by 40 percent after Autopilot was installed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In June 2015, Google confirmed that 12 vehicles had suffered collisions as of that date.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Eight involved rear-end collisions at a stop sign or traffic light, in two of which the vehicle was side-swiped by another driver, one in which another driver rolled a stop sign, and one where a driver was controlling the car manually.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In July 2015, three employees suffered minor injuries when their vehicle was rear-ended by a car whose driver failed to brake.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] This was the first collision that resulted in injuries.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] According to Google Waymo's accident reports as of early 2016, their test cars had been involved in 14 collisions, of which other drivers were at fault 13 times, although in 2016 the car's software caused a crash.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] On 14 February 2016 a Google vehicle attempted to avoid sandbags blocking its path.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Google stated, "In this case, we clearly bear some responsibility, because if our car hadn't moved, there wouldn't have been a collision." Google characterized the crash as a misunderstanding and a learning experience.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A 2017 NTSB investigation documented a low‑speed collision involving an autonomous shuttle in Las Vegas, illustrating early deployment challenges with AV.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In March 2018, Elaine Herzberg died after she was hit by an AC tested by Uber's Advanced Technologies Group (ATG) in Arizona.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Herzberg was crossing the road about 400 feet from an intersection.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Some experts said a human driver could have avoided the crash.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Arizona governor Doug Ducey suspended the company's ability to test its ACs citing an "unquestionable failure" of Uber to protect public safety.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Uber also stopped testing in California until receiving a new permit in 2020.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The NTSB's final report determined that the immediate cause of the accident was that safety driver Rafaela Vasquez failed to monitor the road, because she was distracted by her phone, but that Uber's "inadequate safety culture" contributed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The report noted that the victim had "a very high level" of methamphetamine in her body.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The board called on federal regulators to carry out a review before allowing automated test vehicles to operate on public roads.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In September 2020, Vasquez pled guilty to endangerment and was sentenced to three years' probation.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] On 12 August 2021, a 31-year-old Chinese man was killed after his NIO ES8 crashed in a tunnel.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] NIO's self-driving feature was in beta and could not deal with static obstacles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The vehicle's manual clearly stated that the driver must take over near construction sites.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Lawyers of the deceased's family questioned NIO's private access to the vehicle, which they argued did not guarantee the integrity of the data.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In November 2021, the California Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) notified Pony.ai that it was suspending its testing permit following a reported collision in Fremont on 28 October.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In May 2022, DMV revoked Pony.ai's permit for failing to monitor the driving records of its safety drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In April 2022, Cruise's testing vehicle was reported to have blocked a fire engine on emergency call, and sparked questions about its ability to handle unexpected circumstances.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In February 2024, a driver using the Ford BlueCruise hands-free driving feature struck and killed the driver of a stationary car with no lights on in the middle lane of a freeway in Texas.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In March 2024, a drunk driver who was speeding, holding her cell phone, and using BlueCruise on a Pennsylvania freeway struck and killed two people who had been driving two cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The first car had become disabled and was on the left shoulder with part of the car in the left driving lane.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The second driver had parked his car behind the first car presumably to help the first driver.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The NTSB is investigating both incidents.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration began mandating incident reports from autonomous vehicle companies in June 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Some reports cite incidents from as early as August 2019, with current data available through June 17, 2024.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] There have been a total of 3,979 autonomous vehicle incidents (both ADS and ADAS) reported during this timeframe.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] 2,146 of those incidents (53.9%) involved Tesla vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In a 2011 online survey of 2,006 US and UK consumers, 49% said they would be comfortable using a "driverless car".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A 2012 survey of 17,400 vehicle owners found 37% who initially said they would be interested in purchasing a "fully autonomous car".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] However, that figure dropped to 20% if told the technology would cost US$3,000 more.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In a 2012 survey of about 1,000 German drivers, 22% had a positive attitude, 10% were undecided, 44% were skeptical and 24% were hostile.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A 2013 survey of 1,500 consumers across 10 countries found 57% "stated they would be likely to ride in a car controlled entirely by technology that does not require a human driver", with Brazil, India and China the most willing to trust automated technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In a 2014 US telephone survey, over three-quarters of licensed drivers said they would consider buying a self-driving car, rising to 86% if car insurance were cheaper.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] 31.7% said they would not continue to drive once an automated car was available.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2015, a survey of 5,000 people from 109 countries reported that average respondents found manual driving the most enjoyable.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] 22% did not want to pay more money for autonomy.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Respondents were found to be most concerned about hacking/misuse, and were also concerned about legal issues and safety.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Finally, respondents from more developed countries were less comfortable with their vehicle sharing data.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The survey reported consumer interest in purchasing an AC, stating that 37% of surveyed current owners were either "definitely" or "probably" interested.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2016, a survey of 1,603 people in Germany that controlled for age, gender, and education reported that men felt less anxiety and more enthusiasm, whereas women showed the opposite.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] The difference was pronounced between young men and women and decreased with age.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In a 2016 US survey of 1,584 people, "66 percent of respondents said they think autonomous cars are probably smarter than the average human driver".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] People were worried about safety and hacking risk.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Nevertheless, only 13% of the interviewees saw no advantages in this new kind of cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In a 2017 survey of 4,135 US adults found that many Americans anticipated significant impacts from various automation technologies including the widespread adoption of automated vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2019, a test of a method of surveying opinions about self-driving cars, termed the Autonomous Vehicle Acceptance Model (AVAM), found that users were less accepting of high autonomy levels and displayed significantly lower intention to use highly autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] Additionally, partial autonomy (regardless of level) was perceived as requiring uniformly higher driver engagement (usage of hands, feet and eyes) than full autonomy.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] In 2022, a survey found that 27% of the world's population would feel safe in a self-driving car.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p01] A July 2024 biannual YouGov survey of British adults found that 4% would feel "very safe" in a self-driving car while 37% would feel "very unsafe".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Regulation of self-driving cars refers to legislation passed in various jurisdictions around the world to regulate, standardise, test and monitor the use of autonomous vehicles and automated driving systems on public roads.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Existing liability laws are also evolving to fairly identify the parties responsible for damage and injury, and to address the potential for conflicts of interest between human occupants, system operators, insurers, and the public purse.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Autonomous vehicle regulations may also apply to robotaxis and self-driving trucks, depending upon local legislation.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In June 2011, the US state of Nevada became the first jurisdiction in the world to legislate for self-driving.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Since then, many state, national and supranational bodies have introduced similar laws with varying characteristics.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Regulations governing the testing of automated cars on public roads (as opposed to full consumer operations) include those introduced by the government of the United Kingdom in 2013, with similar laws coming into effect in France in 2015.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Modification of existing international agreements on the use of vehicles on public roads has also taken place.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] The 1949 Vienna Geneva Convention on Road Traffic had assumed that a driver is always fully in control and responsible for the behaviour of a vehicle in traffic, but this was amended in 2016 to allow the possibility of automated features in vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Individual jurisdictions around the world have also set up legal frameworks of various kinds.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] China introduced testing regulations for autonomous cars in 2018, and in 2020 issued the "Strategy for Innovation and Development of Intelligent Vehicles", a roadmap plan until 2025 relating to road traffic safety, surveying and mapping laws relating to intelligent vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In Europe, Regulation 2019/2144, commonly known as the General Safety Regulation (GSR), came into force for all new cars in the European Union after 6th July 2022.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Similar legislation followed in Japan with the law modified to reflect the finalized UNECE WP.29 GRVA regulations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] SAE wording is generally adopted as the de facto standard for definitions in regulations throughout most jurisdictions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] This gives descriptions for levels of autonomy ranging from fully manual (Level 0) to fully automated (Level 5).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Terminology in ADS, Operational Design Domain (ODD) and Dynamic Driving Task (DDT) is also used.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] While various models of car may be described by their manufacturers as being at a certain level, the SAE technical specification means that a car can move between levels depending on the driving task and the circumstances it is operating in at a given time.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] This means that, for example, when a manufacturer says they have a "Level 4 car," they mean the vehicle has one or more specific *features* (like automated valet parking) that are capable of operating at Level 4, but on the open highway they might operate at a lower level.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] As of 2023 most commercially available ADAS vehicles are SAE Level 2.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] A couple of companies reached higher levels, but only in restricted (geofenced) locations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Vehicles operating below Level 5 still offer many advantages.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] SAE Level 2 features are available as part of the ADAS systems in many vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In the US, 50% of new cars provide driver assistance for both steering and speed.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Ford started offering BlueCruise service on certain vehicles in 2022; the system is named ActiveGlide in Lincoln vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] The system provided features such as lane centering, street sign recognition, and hands-free highway driving on more than 130,000 miles of divided highways.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] The 2022 1.2 version added features including hands-free lane changing, in-lane repositioning, and predictive speed assist.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In April 2023 BlueCruise was approved in the UK for use on certain motorways, starting with 2023 models of Ford's electric Mustang Mach-E SUV.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Tesla's Autopilot and its Full Self-Driving (FSD) ADAS suites are available on all Tesla cars since 2016.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] FSD offers highway and street driving (without geofencing), navigation/turn management, steering, and dynamic cruise control, collision avoidance, lane-keeping/switching, emergency braking, obstacle avoidance, but still requires the driver to remain ready to control the vehicle at any moment.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Its driver management system combines eye tracking with monitoring pressure on the steering wheel to ensure that drives are both eyes on and hands on.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Tesla's FSD rewrite V12 (released in March 2024) uses a single deep learning transformer model for all aspects of perception, monitoring, and control.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] It relies on its eight cameras for its vision-only perception system, without use of LiDAR, radar, or ultrasound.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] As of January 2024, Tesla has not initiated requests for Level 3 status for its systems and has not disclosed its reason for not doing so.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] General Motors is developing the "Ultra Cruise" ADAS system, that will be a dramatic improvement over their current "Super Cruise" system.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Ultra Cruise will cover "95 percent" of driving scenarios on 2 million miles of roads in the US, according to the company.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] The system hardware in and around the car includes multiple cameras, short- and long-range radar, and a LiDAR sensor, and will be powered by the Qualcomm Snapdragon Ride Platform.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] The luxury Cadillac Celestiq electric vehicle will be one of the first vehicles to feature Ultra Cruise.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] As of April 2024, two car manufacturers have sold or leased Level 3 cars: Honda in Japan, and Mercedes in Germany, Nevada and California.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Mercedes Drive Pilot has been available on the EQS and S-class sedan in Germany since 2022, and in California and Nevada since 2023.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] A subscription costs between €5,000 and €7,000 for three years in Germany and $2,500 for one year in the United States.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Drive Pilot can only be used when the vehicle is traveling under 40 miles per hour (64 km/h), there is a vehicle in front, readable line markings, during the day, clear weather, and on freeways mapped by Mercedes down to the centimeter (100,000 miles in California).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] As of April 2024, one Mercedes vehicle with this capability has been sold in California.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] As of 2026, the only Level 3 cars in China are Deepal SL03 and Arcfox αS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Honda continued to enhance its Level 3 technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] As of 2023, 80 vehicles with Level 3 support had been sold.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Mercedes-Benz received authorization in early 2023 to pilot its Level 3 software in Las Vegas.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] California also authorized Drive Pilot in 2023.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In 2023 BMW stated that its Level 3 technology was nearing release.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] It would be the second manufacturer to deliver Level 3 technology, but the only one with a Level 3 technology which works in the dark.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In 2023, in China, IM Motors, Mercedes, and BMW obtained authorization to test vehicles with Level 3 systems on motorways.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In September 2021, Stellantis presented its findings from its Level 3 pilot testing on Italian highways.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Stellantis's Highway Chauffeur claimed Level 3 capabilities, as tested on the Maserati Ghibli and Fiat 500X prototypes.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Polestar, a Volvo Cars' brand, announced in January 2022 its plan to offer Level 3 autonomous driving system in the Polestar 3 SUV, a Volvo XC90 successor, with technologies from Luminar Technologies, Nvidia, and Zenseact.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In January 2022, Bosch and the Volkswagen Group subsidiary CARIAD released a collaboration for autonomous driving up to Level 3.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] This joint development targets Level 4 capabilities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Hyundai Motor Company is enhancing cybersecurity of connected cars to offer a Level 3 self-driving Genesis G90.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] Kia and Hyundai Korean car makers delayed their Level 3 plans, and will not deliver Level 3 vehicles in 2023.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In 2024, companies such as Waymo began offering robotaxi services in parts of the US with fully autonomous vehicles without safety drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] These services all operate at a loss as of 2025, with operating costs of about $4.5–$5.5/km ($7–$9 per mile), compared to $0.6/km ($1 per mile) for personal cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] The consultancy McKinsey estimated that bringing costs down to less than $1.2/km ($2 per mile) would take until 2035.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In April 2023 in Japan, a Level 4 protocol became part of the amended Road Traffic Act.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] ZEN drive Pilot Level 4 made by AIST operates there.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In July 2020, Toyota started public demonstration rides on Lexus LS (fifth generation) based TRI-P4 with Level 4 capability.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In August 2021, Toyota operated a potentially Level 4 service using e-Palette around the Tokyo 2020 Olympic Village.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In September 2020, Mercedes-Benz introduced world's first commercial Level 4 Automated Valet Parking (AVP) system named *Intelligent Park Pilot* for its new S-Class.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In November 2022, Germany's Federal Motor Transport Authority (KBA) approved the system for use at Stuttgart Airport.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In September 2021, Cruise, General Motors, and Honda started a joint testing programme, using Cruise AV.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In 2023, the Origin was put on indefinite hold following Cruise's loss of its operating permit.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] In January 2023, Holon announced an autonomous shuttle during the 2023 Consumer Electronics Show (CES).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/autonomous-car-p02] The company claimed that the vehicle is the world's first Level 4 shuttle built to automotive standard.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The automotive and communications industries, along with the U.S. government, European Union and South Korea are actively promoting V2X and C-V2X as potentially life-saving, pollution-reducing technologies.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Department of Transport has said V2X technologies offer significant transportation safety and mobility benefits.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] NHTSA estimates a minimum of 13% reduction in traffic accidents if a V2V system were implemented, resulting in 439,000 fewer crashes per year.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] V2X technology is already being used in Europe and China.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] There are two standards for dedicated V2X communications depending on the underlying wireless technology being used: (1) WLAN-based, and (2) cellular-based.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The history of working on vehicle-to-vehicle communication projects to increase safety, reduce accidents and driver assistance can be traced back to the 1970s with projects such as the US Electronic Road Guidance System (ERGS) and Japan's CACS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Most milestones in the history of vehicle networks originate from the United States, Europe, and Japan.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Standardization of WLAN-based V2X supersedes that of cellular-based V2X systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] IEEE first published the specification of WLAN-based V2X (IEEE 802.11p) in 2010.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It supports direct communication between vehicles (V2V) and between vehicles and infrastructure (V2I).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] This technology is referred to as dedicated short-range communication (DSRC).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] DSRC uses the underlying radio communication provided by 802.11p.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 2016, Toyota became the first automaker globally to introduce automobiles equipped with V2X.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] These vehicles use DSRC technology and are only for sale in Japan.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 2017, GM became the second automaker to introduce V2X.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] GM sells a Cadillac model in the United States that also is equipped with DSRC V2X.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 2016, 3GPP published V2X specifications based on LTE as the underlying technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It is generally referred to as "cellular V2X" (C-V2X) to differentiate itself from the 802.11p based V2X technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In addition to the direct communication (V2V, V2I), C-V2X also supports wide area communication over a cellular network (V2N).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] As of December 2017, a European automotive manufacturer has announced to deploy V2X technology based on 802.11p from 2019.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] This technology can be misused to remotely control the vehicle.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The Police of the Czech Republic in cooperation with universities has developed a system for remote stopping of vehicles with reference to the fact that such a procedure is legal even under the current legislation.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The original V2X communication uses WLAN technology and works directly between vehicles (V2V) as well as vehicles and traffic infrastructure (V2I), which form a vehicular ad-hoc network as two V2X senders come within each other's range.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Hence it does not require any communication infrastructure for vehicles to communicate, which is key to assure safety in remote or little-developed areas.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] WLAN is particularly well-suited for V2X communication, due to its low latency.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It transmits messages known as Cooperative Awareness Messages (CAM) or Basic Safety Message (BSM), and Decentralised Environmental Notification Messages (DENM).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Other roadside infrastructure related messages are Signal Phase and Timing Message (SPaT), In Vehicle Information Message (IVI), and Service Request Message (SRM).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The data volume of these messages is very low.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The radio technology is part of the WLAN IEEE 802.11 family of standards and known in the US as Wireless Access in Vehicular Environments (WAVE) and in Europe as ITS-G5.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] To complement the direct communication mode, vehicles can be equipped with traditional cellular communication technologies, supporting V2N based services.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] This extension with V2N was achieved in Europe under the C-ITS platform umbrella with cellular systems and broadcast systems (TMC/DAB+).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] More recent V2X communication uses cellular networks and is called cellular V2X (or C-V2X) to differentiate it from the WLAN-based V2X.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] There have been multiple industry organizations, such as the 5G Automotive Association (5GAA) promoting C-V2X due to its advantages over WLAN based V2X (without considering disadvantages at the same time).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 3GPP Release 15, the V2X functionalities are expanded to support 5G.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] C-V2X includes support of both direct communication between vehicles (V2V) and traditional cellular-network based communication.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Also, C-V2X provides a migration path to 5G based systems and services, which implies incompatibility and higher costs compared to 4G based solutions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The direct communication between vehicle and other devices (V2V, V2I) uses so-called PC5 interface.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] PC5 refers to a reference point where the User Equipment (UE), i.e. mobile handset, directly communicates with another UE over the direct channel.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In this case, the communication with the base station is not required.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In system architectural level, proximity service (ProSe) is the feature that specifies the architecture of the direct communication between UEs.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 3GPP RAN specifications, "sidelink" is the terminology to refer to the direct communication over PC5.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] PC5 interface was originally defined to address the needs of mission-critical communication for public safety community (Public Safety-LTE, or PS-LTE) in release 13.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The motivation of the mission-critical communication was to allow law enforcement agencies or emergency rescue to use the LTE communication even when the infrastructure is not available, such as natural disaster scenario.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In release 14 onwards, the use of PC5 interface has been expanded to meet various market needs, such as communication involving wearable devices such as smartwatch.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In C-V2X, PC5 interface is re-applied to the direct communication in V2V and V2I.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The Cellular V2X mode 4 communication relies on a distributed resource allocation scheme, namely sensing-based semipersistent scheduling which schedules radio resources in a stand-alone fashion in each user equipment (UE).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In addition to the direct communication over PC5, C-V2X also allows the C-V2X device to use the cellular network connection in the traditional manner over Uu interface.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Uu refers to the logical interface between the UE and the base station.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] This is generally referred to as vehicle-to-network (V2N), the mechanism that enables conventional **telematics** services.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] V2N is a unique use case to C-V2X and does not exist in 802.11p based V2X given that the latter supports direct communication only.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] However, similar to WLAN based V2X also in case of C-V2X, two communication radios are required to be able to communicate simultaneously via a PC5 interface with nearby stations and via the UU interface with the network.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] While 3GPP defines the data transport features that enable V2X, it does not include V2X semantic content but proposes usage of ITS-G5 standards like CAM, DENM, BSM, etc. over 3GPP V2X data transport features.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Department of Transportation announced that it is awarding $60 million in grants to advance connected and interoperable vehicle technologies under a program called "Saving Lives with Connectivity: Accelerating V2X Deployment program".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It said the grants to recipients in Arizona, Texas and Utah would serve as national models to accelerate and spur new deployments of V2X technologies.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] European standardisation body ETSI and SAE published standards on what they see as use cases.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Early use cases focus on road safety and efficiency.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Organizations such as 3GPP and 5GAA continuously introduce and test new cases.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The 5GAA has published several roadmaps which highlight the technical potential and challenges of new use cases.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Some use cases address high levels of automation.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] C-V2X offers further use cases including slippery road, roadworks and road hazard information to cars and trucks over hills, around curves and over longer distances than is possible with direct communications.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Volvo, for example, has sold new cars that warn other Volvos of slippery roads ahead using C-V2X communications since 2016 in Denmark, and has announced plans to complement that with general accident-ahead warnings and offer the same functionality in other European markets over time.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In the medium term, V2X is perceived as a key enabler for autonomous driving, assuming it would be allowed to intervene into the actual driving.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In that case, vehicles would be able to join platoons the way HGVs do.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Hobbyists have documented open source projects capturing V2X packets or plotting passing vehicle speeds.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] WLAN-based V2X communication is based on a set of standards drafted by the American Society for Testing and Materials (ASTM).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The ASTM E 2213 series of standards looks at wireless communication for high-speed information exchange between vehicles themselves as well as road infrastructure.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The first standard of this series was published 2002.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Here the acronym Wireless Access in Vehicular Environments (WAVE) was first used for V2X communication.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] From 2004 onwards the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) started to work on wireless access for vehicles under the umbrella of their standards family IEEE 802.11 for Wireless Local Area Networks (WLAN).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Their initial standard for wireless communication for vehicles is known as IEEE 802.11p and is based on the work done by the ASTM.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Later on in 2012 IEEE 802.11p was incorporated in IEEE 802.11.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Around 2007 when IEEE 802.11p got stable, IEEE started to develop the 1609.x standards family standardising applications and a security framework (IEEE uses the term WAVE), and soon after SAE started to specify standards for V2V communication applications.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] SAE uses the term DSRC for this technology (this is how the term was coined in the US).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In parallel at ETSI the technical committee for Intelligent transportation system (ITS) was founded and started to produce standards for protocols and applications (ETSI coined the term ITS-G5).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] All these standards are based on IEEE 802.11p technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Between 2012 and 2013, the Japanese Association of Radio Industries and Businesses (ARIB) specified, also based on IEEE 802.11, a V2V and V2I communication system in the 700 MHz frequency band.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 2015 ITU published as summary of all V2V and V2I standards that are worldwide in use, comprising the systems specified by ETSI, IEEE, ARIB, and TTA (Republic of Korea, Telecommunication Technology Association).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] 3GPP started standardization work of cellular V2X (C-V2X) in Release 14 in 2014.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It is based on LTE as the underlying technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Because this C-V2X functionalities are based on LTE, it is often referred to as LTE-V2X.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The scope of functionalities supported by C-V2X includes both direct communication (V2V, V2I) as well as wide area cellular network communication (V2N).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In Release 15, 3GPP continued its C-V2X standardization to be based on 5G.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Specifications are published in 2018 as Release 15 comes to completion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] To indicate the underlying technology, the term 5G-V2X is often used in contrast to LTE-based V2X (LTE-V2X).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Either case, C-V2X is the generic terminology that refers to the V2X technology using the cellular technology irrespective of the specific generation of technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In Release 16, 3GPP further enhances the C-V2X functionality.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In this way, C-V2X is inherently future-proof by supporting migration path to 5G.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Study and analysis were done to compare the effectiveness of direct communication technologies between LTE-V2X PC5 and 802.11p from the perspective of accident avoided and reduction in fatal and serious injuries.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The study shows that LTE-V2X achieves higher level of accident avoidance and reduction in injury.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It also indicates LTE-V2X performs higher percentage of successful packet delivery and communication range.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Another link-level and system-level simulation result indicates that, to achieve the same link performance for both line-of-sight (LOS) and non-line-of-sight (NLOS) scenarios, lower signal-to-noise-ratio (SNR) are achievable by LTE-V2X PC5 interface compared to IEEE 802.11p.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Cellular-based V2X solution also leads to the possibility of further protecting other types of road users (e.g. pedestrian, cyclist) by having PC5 interface to be integrated into smartphones, effectively integrating those road users into the overall C-ITS solution.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Vehicle-to-person (V2P) includes Vulnerable Road User (VRU) scenarios to detect pedestrians and cyclists to avoid accident and injuries involving those road users.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] As both direct communication and wide area cellular network communication are defined in the same standard (3GPP), both modes of communication will likely be integrated into a single chipset.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Commercialization of those chipsets further enhances economy of scale and leads to possibilities to wider range of business models and services using both types of communications.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 1999 the US Federal Communications Commission (FCC) allocated 75 MHz in the spectrum of 5.850-5.925 GHz for intelligent transport systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Since then the US Department of Transportation (USDOT) has been working with a range of stakeholders on V2X.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 2012 a pre-deployment project was implemented in Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] 2800 vehicles covering cars, motorcycles, buses and HGV of different brands took part using equipment by different manufacturers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) saw this model deployment as proof that road safety could be improved and that WAVE standard technology was interoperable.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In August 2014 NHTSA published a report arguing vehicle-to-vehicle technology was technically proven as ready for deployment.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] On 20 August 2014 the NHTSA published an Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (ANPRM) in the Federal Register, arguing that the safety benefits of V2X communication could only be achieved if a significant part of the vehicles fleet was equipped.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Because of the lack of an immediate benefit for early adopters, the NHTSA proposed a mandatory introduction.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] On 25 June 2015 the US House of Representatives held a hearing on the matter, where again the NHTSA, as well as other stakeholders argued the case for V2X.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] On November 18, 2020, the FCC reallocated 45 MHz in the 5.850–5.895 GHz range to Wi-Fi, and the rest of the V2X band to C-V2X, citing the failure of DSRC to take off.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The advocacy organizations ITS America and American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials sued the FCC, arguing that the decision harms users of DSRC; on August 12, 2022, a federal court permitted the reassignment to go ahead.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] To acquire EU-wide spectrum, radio applications require a harmonised standard, in case of ITS-G5 ETSI EN 302 571, first published in 2008.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] A harmonised standard in turn requires an ETSI System Reference Document, here ETSI TR 101 788.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Commission Decision 2008/671/EC harmonises the use of the 5875 to 5905 MHz frequency band for transport safety ITS applications.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 2010 the ITS Directive 2010/40/EU was adopted.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It aims to assure that ITS applications are interoperable and can operate across national borders, it defines priority areas for secondary legislation, which cover V2X and requires technologies to be mature.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 2014 the European Commission's industry stakeholder “C-ITS Deployment Platform” started working on a regulatory framework for V2X in the EU.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It identified key approaches to an EU-wide V2X security Public Key infrastructure (PKI) and data protection, as well as facilitating a mitigation standard to prevent radio interference between ITS-G5 based V2X and road charging systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The European Commission recognised ITS-G5 as the initial communication technology in its 5G Action Plan and the accompanying explanatory document, to form a communication environment consisting of ITS-G5 and cellular communication as envisioned by EU Member States.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Various pre-deployment projects exist at EU or EU Member State level, such as SCOOP@F, the Testfeld Telematik, the digital testbed Autobahn, the Rotterdam-Vienna ITS Corridor, Nordic Way, COMPASS4D or C-ROADS.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] There exist real scenarios of implementation V2X standard as well.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The first commercial project where V2X standard is used for Intersection movement assist use-case.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] It has been realized in Brno City / Czech Republic where 80 pcs of cross intersections are controlled by V2X communication standard from public transport vehicles of municipality Brno.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Spectrum allocation for C-ITS in various countries is shown in the following table.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] Due to the standardization of V2X in 802.11p preceding C-V2X standardization in 3GPP, spectrum allocation was originally intended for the 802.11p based system.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] However, the regulations are technology neutral so that the deployment of C-V2X is not excluded.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In 2022, US Federal Courts told the FCC that it could reallocate 45 MHz of V2X spectrum to wireless and cellular carriers, citing years of no use by V2X constituents.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The deployment of V2X technology (either C-V2X or 802.11p based products) will occur gradually over time.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] New cars will be equipped with either of the two technologies starting around 2020 and its proportion on the road is expected to increase gradually.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The Volkswagen Golf 8th generation was the first passenger car to be fitted with V2X technology powered by NXP technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] In the meantime, existing (legacy) vehicles will continue to exist on the road.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] This implies that the V2X capable vehicles will need to co-exist with non-V2X (legacy) vehicles or with V2X vehicles of incompatible technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] The main obstacles to its adoption are legal issues and the fact that, unless almost all vehicles adopt it, its effectiveness is limited.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] British weekly *The Economist* argued in 2016 that autonomous driving is more driven by regulations than by technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/vehicle-to-everything] However, a 2017 study indicated that there are benefits in reducing traffic accidents even during the transitional period in which the technology is being adopted in the market.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The company traces its origins to the Stanford Racing Team, which competed in the 2005 and 2007 Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) Grand Challenges.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Google's development of self-driving technology began in January 2009 and the project was revealed in October 2010.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In December 2016, the project was renamed Waymo and spun out of Google as part of Alphabet.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In October 2020, Waymo became the first company to offer service to the public without safety drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo is run by co-CEOs Tekedra Mawakana and Dmitri Dolgov since April 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The company raised $11 billion in multiple outside funding rounds by 2024.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In February 2026, Waymo raised $16 billion, which valued the company at $126 billion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Google's development of self-driving technology began on January 17, 2009, at Google X lab, run by Google co-founder Sergey Brin.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The project was launched at Google by Sebastian Thrun, the former director of the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory (SAIL) and Anthony Levandowski, founder of 510 Systems and Anthony's Robots.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Later, aspects of this technology were used in a digital mapping project for SAIL called VuTool.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2007, Google acqui-hired the entire VuTool team to help advance Google's Street View technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] As part of Street View development, 100 Toyota Priuses were outfitted with Topcon digital mapping hardware developed by 510 Systems.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2008, the Street View team launched project Ground Truth, to create accurate road maps by extracting data from satellites and street views.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In February 2008, a Discovery Channel producer for the documentary series *Prototype This!* phoned Levandowski.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The producer requested to borrow Levandowski's Ghost Rider, the autonomous two-wheeled motorcycle Levandowski's Berkeley team had built for the 2004 DARPA Grand Challenge that Levandowski had later donated to the Smithsonian.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Since the motorcycle was not available, Levandowski offered to retrofit a Toyota Prius as a self-driving pizza delivery car for the show.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] As a Google employee, Levandowski asked Larry Page and Thrun whether Google was interested in participating in the show.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] However, they authorized Levandowski to move forward with the project, as long as it was not associated with Google.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Within weeks Levandowski founded Anthony's Robots to do so.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] He retrofitted the car with light detection and ranging (lidar) technology, sensors, and cameras.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The Stanford team behind the Stanley car provided its code base to the project.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The ensuing episode depicting Pribot delivering pizza across the San Francisco Bay Bridge under police escort aired in December 2008.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The project success led Google to greenlight Google's self-driving car program in January 2009.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2011, Google acquired 510 Systems (co-founded by Levandowski, Pierre-Yves Droz and Andrew Schultz), and Anthony's Robots for an estimated US$20 million.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Levandowski's vehicle and hardware, and Stanford's AI technology and software, became the nucleus of the project.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] After almost two years of road testing with seven vehicles, the *New York Times* revealed the existence of Google's project on October 9, 2010.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Google announced its initiative later the same day.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Starting in 2010, lawmakers in various states expressed concerns over how to regulate autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] A related Nevada law went into effect on March 1, 2012.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] A modified Prius was licensed by the Nevada Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) in May 2012.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The car was "driven" by Chris Urmson with Levandowski in the passenger seat.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] This was the first US license for a self-driven car.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In January 2014 Google was granted a patent for a transportation service funded by advertising that included autonomous vehicles as a transport method.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In late May, Google revealed an autonomous prototype, which had no steering wheel, gas pedal, or brake pedal.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In December, Google unveiled a Firefly prototype that was planned to be tested on San Francisco Bay Area roads beginning in early 2015.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In August 2015, Google hired former Hyundai Motor executive, John Krafcik, as CEO.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In fall 2015, Google for the first time to non-employees provided a ride in a fully autonomous vehicle in Austin, Texas.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] It was the first entirely autonomous trip on a public road.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] It was not accompanied by a test driver or police escort.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The car had no steering wheel or floor pedals.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] By the end of 2015, Project Chauffeur had covered more than a million miles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Google spent $1.1 billion on the project between 2009 and 2015.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] For comparison, the acquisition of Cruise Automation by General Motors in March 2016 was for $500 million, and Uber's acquisition of Otto in August 2016 was for $680 million.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In May 2016, Google and Stellantis announced an order of 100 Chrysler Pacifica hybrid minivans to test the self-driving technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In December 2016, the project changed its name to Waymo and spun out of Google as part of Alphabet.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The name was derived from "a new way forward in mobility".
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In May 2016, the company opened a 53,000-square-foot (4,900 m2) technology center in Novi, Michigan.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In February 2017, Waymo sued Uber and its subsidiary self-driving trucking company, Otto, alleging trade secret theft and patent infringement.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The company claimed that three ex-Google employees, including Anthony Levandowski, had stolen trade secrets, including thousands of files, from Google before joining Uber.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The alleged infringement was related to Waymo's proprietary lidar technology, Google accused Uber of colluding with Levandowski.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Levandowski allegedly downloaded 9 gigabytes of data that included over a hundred trade secrets; eight of which were at stake during the trial.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] An ensuing settlement gave Waymo 0.34% of Uber stock, the equivalent of $245 million.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Uber agreed not to infringe Waymo's intellectual property.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Part of the agreement included a guarantee that "Waymo confidential information is not being incorporated in Uber Advanced Technologies Group hardware and software." In statements released after the settlement, Uber maintained that it received no trade secrets.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In May, according to an Uber spokesman, Uber had fired Levandowski, which resulted in the loss of roughly $250 million of his equity in Uber, which almost exactly equaled the settlement.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Uber announced that it was halting production of self-driving trucks through Otto in July 2018, and the subsidiary company was shuttered.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2020, Levandowski pled guilty to one of 33 charges, and was sentenced to 18 months in prison.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo began testing minivans without a safety driver on public roads in Chandler, Arizona, in October 2017.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2017, Waymo unveiled new sensors and chips that are less expensive to manufacture, cameras that improve visibility, and wipers to clear the lidar system.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] At the beginning of the self-driving car program, they used a $75,000 lidar system from Velodyne.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2017, the cost decreased approximately 90 percent, as Waymo converted to in-house built lidar.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo has applied its technology to various cars including the Prius, Audi TT, Chrysler Pacifica, and Lexus RX450h.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo partners with Lyft on pilot projects and product development.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo started testing in Phoenix without safety drivers in November 2017.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In March 2018, Jaguar Land Rover announced that Waymo had ordered up to 20,000 of its I-Pace electric SUVs at an estimated cost of more than $1 billion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In late May 2018, Alphabet announced plans to add up to 62,000 Pacifica Hybrid minivans to the fleet.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Also in May 2018, Waymo established Huimo Business Consulting subsidiary in Shanghai.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In October 2018, the California Department of Motor Vehicles issued a permit for Waymo to operate cars without safety drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo was the first company to receive a permit for day and night testing on public roads and highways.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo announced that its service would include Mountain View, Sunnyvale, Los Altos, and Palo Alto.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In July 2019, Waymo received permission to transport passengers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In December 2018, Waymo launched Waymo One in Phoenix, transporting passengers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The service used safety drivers to monitor some rides, with others provided in select areas without them.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In November 2019, Waymo One became the first autonomous service worldwide to operate without safety drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo One launched in San Francisco, beginning with a "trusted tester" rollout.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In March 2022, Waymo began offering rides for Waymo staff in San Francisco without a safety driver.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In April 2019, Waymo announced plans for vehicle assembly in Detroit at the former American Axle & Manufacturing plant, bringing between 100 and 400 jobs to the area.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo used vehicle assembler Magna to turn Jaguar I-PACE electric SUVs and Chrysler Pacifica Hybrid minivans into Waymo Level 4 autonomous vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo subsequently reverted to retrofitting existing models rather than a custom design.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In March 2020, Waymo Via was launched after the company's announcement that it had raised $2.25 billion from investors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In May 2020, Waymo raised an additional $750 million.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In July 2020, the company announced an exclusive partnership with auto manufacturer Volvo to integrate Waymo technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In April 2021, Krafcik was replaced by two co-CEOs: Waymo's COO Tekedra Mawakana and CTO Dmitri Dolgov.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Mawakana is responsible for business operations, and Dolgov is responsible for the company's technology.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo raised $2.5 billion in another funding round in June 2021, with total funding of $5.5 billion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo launched a consumer testing program in San Francisco in August 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In May 2022, Waymo started a pilot program seeking riders in downtown Phoenix, Arizona.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In May 2022, Waymo announced that it would expand the program to more areas of Phoenix.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2023, coverage of the Waymo One area was increased by 45 square miles (120 km2), expanding to include downtown Mesa, uptown Phoenix, and South Mountain Village.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In June 2022, Waymo announced a partnership with Uber, under which Waymo will integrate its autonomous technology into Uber's freight truck service.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Plans to expand the program to Los Angeles were announced in late 2022.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] On December 13, 2022, Waymo applied for the final permit necessary to operate fully autonomous taxis, without a backup driver present, within the state of California.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In January 2023, *The Information* reported that Waymo staff were among those affected by Google's layoffs of around 12,000 workers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] *TechCrunch* reported that Waymo was set to kill its trucking program.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In July 2024, Waymo began testing its sixth-generation robotaxis which are based on electric vehicles by Chinese automobile company Zeekr, developed in a partnership first announced in 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] They were anticipated to reduce costs, at a time when Waymo was operating at a loss.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In October 2024, Waymo closed a $5.6 billion funding round led by Alphabet, aimed at expanding its robotaxi services, bringing its total capital to over $11 billion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Around that time, the New York Times described Waymo as being "far ahead of the competition", in particular after Cruise had to suspend its operations after an accident in 2023.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In November 2025, Waymo introduced freeway travel for select riders.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo paused all freeway service in May 2026.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Also in November 2025, the permit area in Northern California was expanded to include Santa Rosa and Sacramento.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The Southern California permit area was expanded to stretch from the Mexican border to Ventura County.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] These new permit areas were approved by the California Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The permit area of the DMV is larger than the operating area.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The operating area is slated to get expanded to cover San Diego in mid-2026.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In February 2026, Waymo raised a $16 billion funding round that valued the company at $126 billion, to fund further expansion into new markets.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Bloomberg reported that $13 billion of that came from Alphabet.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo regularly lobbies public officials and regulators throughout US cities and states, to encourage updates to laws so self-driving vehicles can operate in those locations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2024, Waymo spent $1.7 million on lobbying in the US.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In the state of New York, Waymo has spent $1.8 million since 2019 on lobbying efforts, as of January 2026.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In February 2026, Waymo company representatives spoke to the United States Senate Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation and requested that the federal government create uniform nationwide standards for autonomous vehicle deployment.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The company stated that unless the US reduces regulations that hamper innovation, US companies will lose the trillion dollar global autonomous vehicle market to Chinese companies.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2017, Waymo highlighted four business uses for its autonomous technology: robotaxis; trucking and logistics; urban public transportation; and passenger cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] As of 2023, trucking is no longer a focus.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo currently serves select cities in the United States, and has announced expansion into Japan and the United Kingdom.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The service is accessed in most locations by using the Waymo iOS app or Android app; Waymo service in Austin and Atlanta is available by using the Uber app.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Once a Waymo vehicle arrives, riders push a button to "start ride", and have optional "help", "lock", and "pull over" buttons.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Rides usually complete without riders pressing any optional buttons.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The car's steering wheel turns as the car makes turns, and a passenger may sit in the right-front passenger seat, but not in the driver's seat.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Some information gathered by the car's sensors is displayed on a screen.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] As of March 2026, Waymo has 3,000 robotaxis in service, provides 500,000 paid rides per week, and drives 4 million rider-only miles per week.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In September 2025, Waymo and the city of Chandler, Arizona announced that Waymo would be integrated into Chandler's public microtransit service.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2020 Waymo launched a self-driving truck development division designated as *Waymo Via*, to work with OEMs to integrate its technology into commercial vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The company began testing Class 8 tractor-trailers in 2018 in Atlanta, expanding in 2019 to southwest shipping routes across Arizona, California, New Mexico and Texas.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The company opened a trucking hub in Dallas, Texas in 2021.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] It partnered with Daimler to integrate autonomous technology into a fleet of Freightliner Cascadia trucks.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo operated 48 Class 8 autonomous trucks with safety drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo tested its technology in commercial delivery vehicles with United Parcel Service.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In July 2020 Waymo and Stellantis expanded their partnership, including the development of Ram ProMaster delivery vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In July 2023, Waymo announced that it was moving away from commercial development of self-driving trucks to focus on the ride-hailing Waymo business, and shuttered the Waymo Via trucking program.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The vast majority of employees who were on Waymo's trucking team moved to other roles within the company.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo has partnered with Uber Eats and DoorDash to deliver food.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo data is used by local governments for pothole detection.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Google has invested heavily in matrix multiplication and video processing hardware such as the Tensor Processing Unit (TPU) to augment Nvidia's graphics processing units (GPUs) and Intel's central processing units (CPUs) used in Waymo vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo manufactures a suite of self-driving hardware developed in-house.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] This includes sensors and hardware-enhanced vision system, lidar, and radar.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Sensors give 360-degree views while lidar detects objects up to 300 metres (980 ft) away.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Short-range lidar images objects near the vehicle, and radar is used to see around other vehicles and track objects in motion.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo uses a deep-learning architecture called VectorNet to predict vehicle trajectories in complex traffic scenarios.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] It uses a graph neural network to model the interactions between vehicles and has demonstrated state-of-the-art performance on several benchmark datasets for trajectory prediction.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo Carcraft is a virtual world in which Waymo simulates driving conditions.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The simulator was named after the video game *World of Warcraft*.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] With Carcraft, 25,000 virtual self-driving cars navigate through models of Austin, Texas; Mountain View, California; Phoenix, Arizona; and other cities.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] As of November 2025, most of Waymo's robotaxis are customized Jaguar I-Pace cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo plans to introduce Hyundai Ioniq 5 and Zeekr Ojai cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] As of October 2024, Morgan Stanley estimated the total vehicle cost at over $120,000, and another source estimated $150,000.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] As of June 2025, a third source estimates it to be above $100,000.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Other costs include ride monitors, service personnel, and real estate for storing and servicing the vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In February 2026, Waymo's chief safety officer confirmed that the company employs remote assistance workers in the United States and the Philippines to address situations that the vehicles cannot independently solve.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The company stated that the remote workers do not drive the vehicles, simply providing guidance to the vehicle, which can accept or reject it.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] From California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC) data, as of September 2025, Waymo delivered 4.75 million Passenger Miles Traveled (PMT) monthly, which required 6.57 million Vehicle Miles Traveled (VMT).
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] This is a three-fold growth from September 2024 in both PMT and VMT, with the ratio staying roughly equal.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Vehicles have an average passenger occupancy of 0.75.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 70% of the trips, only one passenger is in the car.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] For 44% of miles, the vehicle is empty, and 4.6% of requested trips are cancelled.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2024, Waymo and insurance company Swiss Re published a study which estimated that Waymo generated 92% fewer bodily injury claims and 88% fewer property damage claims than human drivers over the same number of miles in the same locations.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] The study said that by the end of 2024, the company was facing two potential bodily injury claims (accidents where the Waymo vehicle was potentially at fault), and estimated that human drivers would have generated 26 bodily injury claims.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] For property damage claims, Waymo logged nine versus an estimated 78 for human drivers.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Experts noted that the sample size in the study of 25 million miles driven is extremely small (0.0008%), compared to the 3 trillion miles logged annually by human drivers in the US.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In July 2021, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) started requiring autonomous vehicle companies to report any accidents which result in injury or property damage that occur within 30 seconds of the vehicle operating in autonomous mode.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] As of March 16, 2026, the (NHTSA) has logged 1,790 accidents (cumulative since July 2021), involving Waymo vehicles.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] From July 2021 to January 2025, Waymo's vehicles have been involved in about 30 accidents with injuries, though the NHTSA reports do not ascribe fault.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In September 2025, a Waymo in Atlanta was recorded illegally passing a stopped school bus.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Georgia State Representative Clint Crowe and State Senator Rick Williams criticized Waymo, with Williams stating his support for higher fines for self-driving cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2018, after the death of Elaine Herzberg — the first recorded case of a pedestrian fatality involving a self-driving car (an Uber test vehicle) — there were several cases of Waymo cars being vandalized.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In 2023, the San Francisco group *Safe Street Rebel* used a practice called "coning" to trap Waymo and Cruise cars with traffic cones as a form of protest after stating that the cars had been involved in hundreds of incidents.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In February 2024, during Lunar New Year celebrations in Chinatown, San Francisco, a mob of vandals attacked, graffitied, and set fire to a Waymo car.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In February 2024, a pair of Waymo passengers described an attack by an onlooker who attempted to cover the car's sensors.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] In July 2024, Waymo sued two people who allegedly vandalized their cars.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] During the June 2025 Los Angeles protests against mass deportation, several Waymo cars were set on fire when riots broke out.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Officials including California Governor Gavin Newsom and Los Angeles Mayor Karen Bass condemned the destruction, attributing it to extremists infiltrating otherwise-peaceful protests.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] Waymo has been criticized for the use of its camera footage by law enforcement agencies.
[src:autonomous-vehicles/waymo] According to Waymo, it "does not provide information or data to law enforcement without a valid legal request".
